d stocks, has causeu some uneasi\nness. Quoted opinions of business men\nand bankers on the business outlook,\nhowever, may be characterized as con\nservatively optimistic. It is pointed out\nthat the seasonal recession in some of\nthe basic industries has been le. c\nmarked than usual and that the price\nstructure remains fairly stable,\nRailroad shares were the centers of\nspeculative interest in today\u2019s market.\nThe announcement that a tentative\ndraft of the revised southwestern mer\nger had been prepared brought fresh\nbuying into the shares of the roads\ninvolved, although some of the previous\npurchasers showed a disposition to take\nprofits on the rally. Lehigh Valley ran\nup 6 points to 133 on the publication\nof an optimistic statement by Presi\nFRECKLES AND HIS FRIENDS By Blossei MOM\u2019N POP By Taylor\n\njr? S. 111 'ZABSS ARE OATS- ru_ Do SoaaF-7AIM<S*\nrfrfffiT jI I P \\JtUX AY\u00a3M.VA II Pi I'M (50)206 To PL.AMT 7W^T-=*-\n1 i' i 6or TUPDf= 2 Mil 'EM SO I CAM I\u2019LL ASJk. MY U,MCLt=\n'll waatSSa fl POAiy CLEMWATI\nI VKIAEM ae sets- j SMOOLD do.' y\nJ SOTTUEGEo) IT\u2014 ViJg ALL GOT\n111 ,|l I 'fS -7/\" j 1 70 DO SOAA&7AIM6 }!l\n\u20141\nEAEPYT-UMS, W TELL MY POP AE PLAVSD J\nmore\u2019as r\"^yT 7AE po/oies e\\jer y* t t\nA/OVBODV I/O TttlS v\u2014/ AOVM do SI/OCE ME U/AS J\n-1\nREG. O. S. PAT. OFF.\nTHE GU MP S \u2014SW EET CHARITY\n~r\\' O /gosh.\u2019~\nDOUGLAS DAILY DISPATCH, SUNDAY MORNING, JUNE 19, 1927.\ndent Loomis, but it later sold down to\n12714. Western Pacific was run up\n3% points to 37 -li, but failed to main\ntain all of its gain.\nSimultaneous strength of Pittsburgh\nand West Virginia, Pittsburgh Coal and\nPittsburgh Terminal Coal, all of which\nscored extreme gains of 4 to 6 points,\nled to the belief that buying was for\nthe account of identical interests, be\nlieved in some quarters to be the Van\nSweringens. The name of William C.\nDuraqt was brought forward by one of\nthe financial tickers as a buyer of New\nHaven, the .recent advance in which\nalso has been associated with the re\nports of a refunding of the road\u2019s debt\nto the government.\nAmong the many issues to reach hew\nhigh ground were St. Paul preferred,\nNew York, Ontario and Western, In\ntertype corporation. Eaton Axle, Viva\ndou, Transcontinental Oil and White\nSewing Machine. One block of 17,500\nshares of Consolidated Textile changed\nhands at 7, with subsequent sales set\nting a new 1927 top above that figure.\nWhite Motors broke several points to\na new low at 42\u2019- and brought sym\npathetic selling into Mack Trucks. Yel\nlow Truck and some of the other\nmotors.\nA 10-point jump in Japanese yen and\na drop of 10 '4 in Spanish pesetas were\nthe contrasting features of the for\neign exchange market, the former\nruling around 46.05 cents and the latter\nclose to 17.03. Demand sterling was\nquoted around $4.85 3-16 and French\nirancs just oeiow 3.91 y 2 cents.\nCOTTON MARKET\nNEW YORK, June 18 W.\u2014 Early de\nclines were followed by rallies in the\ncotton market today. 'The government\nreport on boll weevil emergence prior\nto June 1 attracted bullish comment\nwhich probably brought in some buy\ning. After selling off to 16.80. October\ncontracts rallied to 17, closing at 16.97.\nThe general market closed steady at\nnet advances of 10 to 11 points. Cotton\nfutures closed steady, 10 to 12 points\nhigher. Spot quiet; middling 16.90.\no\nLOS ANGELES LIVESTOCK\nLOS ANGELES. June 18 W.\u2014Hogs:\nreceipts 5.200 for week; 25 cents to 35\ncents higher than Monday; top $11.35;\nbulk 150 to 190 pound $11.35; packing\nsows $8.50 to $9.\nCattle: receipts 4,300 for week; good\ngrades active, steady; others slow and\nweak; bulk $7.50 to $8.85; top 8.95;\nbulk she stock $5 to 6.25; top heifers\n$7.50; all cutters $2.75 to $4.50; bulls\n$5.25 to $6. Calves: receipts 750 for\nweek; 25 cents to 50 cents higher; bulk\nvealers $10.50 to sl2; weighty calves\n$7 to $8.50.\nWEEK\u2019S REVIEW\nSHOWS BUT FEW\nPRICE CHANGES\nNEW YORK, June 18 \u00ab>).\u2014Few gen\neral price changes of consequence took\nplace in this week\u2019s financial and se\ncurities market.\nStock prices underwent one of the\nsharpest reactions of the year last\nTuesday as a result of an unexpect\nedly large increase in brokers\u2019 loans the\nweek before but made irregular recov\nery during the rest of the week, with\nthe result that both rail and industrial\naverages shov/ed little net change.\nBond prices eased slightly, with new\nofferings of arqpnd $105,000,000, or only\nabout half of the previous week\u2019s total.\nThe bond market was forced to con\ntend with a large volume of undigested\nnew securities, but with record-break\ning dividends and interest payments to\nbe distributed next month, dealers are\nlooking forward to an investment de\nmand which will clear their shelves.\nf GOOD At'oftWlMdr TTivr'c GCFAT* f* I WANT T 'O TiACK T 'O CAN'T SAV JO\n-1 josr\\ YO A6 \u00b0\u00b0T X A6(?\u00a3\u00a3 wmf\nDRoppeo lu rocer rZSS/Ifii \u00a7HEW/iMteo Ti) dc/ts\nYOOKNOW Domes J BORROW rMOM j g, CkN\u00a3)W/\nreenwe mocm To TbtNK Or we cwt J\nv tsff\nfHJ y N shoulon-'t D/ve. j\nmBLsL- M AND X DOM'TkNOW\nTttCN There\u2019s (khckher You're virong 7he(?e, s C LKnow,mr.<sdnn, eor \\J 'That\u2019s easy O\nA h6LE,TOO- L Crn'T' Too.' .TIE Nice. Tti*rs 6AS/\u00a3f? t&ll \u2019em To\nAFFORD SOtH AM J L&tit\u2019/blR 1 PLACE DONCj\u2014 J Q- YOU\neipeuswer ApAeweNr voo have is Josr promised J Receipts\nASWE HAVE MW- 1 YfHAT DOT Neeos monem 1\nI\u2019LLHAVS TO cor OOP A ToHCLP <3*T DII~XSCNT\nk \u2018ESSSJSrfw' l themeor\u00ab\ni means-move/ j stw wtje&e j' reu, TweiM f y checks\nyou one \\\\csre\u00dfoeH f\nhi...\u2014.- i i M in i..1.M.i.- m\nThe shifting of funds incidental to\nfederal income tax and other mid\nmonth payments and government\nfinancing failed to disturb the money\nmarket, which continued relatively\ni easy. The renewal rate on call money\ndropped to 4 per cent on Friday, the\nlowest opening rate in about 3 weeks,\nwith funds available in the \u201coutside\nmarket\u201d that day as low as 3%.\nCommodity markets were mixed.\nWheat and cotton futures drifted\nslightly lower, while coffee and sugar\nquotations improved.\nThe principal foreign exchanges held\nfairly steady, with a moderate improve\nment in Japanese yen being accom\npanied by reports of the early flotation\nof a loan to the city of Osaxa.\nGRAINMARKET\nCHICAGO, June 18 W.\u2014Rains in\nthe wheat harvest region southwest,\ntogether with unfavorable corn crop\nadvices, led to upturns today both for\nwheat and corn. Wheat closed firm,\ncent to 1 cent net higher; corn\ncent to 7 it cent up; oats at V\u00bb cent to\ncent advance, and provisions un\nchanged to 5 cents lower.\nWheat traders showed particular\nnervousness over reports of Kansas\nrains being so heavy that new floods\nwere threatened and that river banks\nwere being dynamited. Word was also\nreceived that in places the downpour\namounted to 5% inches and that in\neastern Kansas harvesting had been\nstopped. Showery weather over spring\nwheat territory south and north of the\nCanadian boundary was also construed\nin some quarters as bullish and so too\nwas a Winnipeg report that between\n2,000,000 and 3,000,000 acres seeded in\nCanada since June 1 would require\nvery favorable weather to mature.\nIn addition to the fact that the\ngovernment forecast suggested unwel\ncome showers over a good part of the\ncorn belt, renewed buying in the com\nmarket was given a stimulus through\nthe circumstance that the general run\nof corn crop news was bullish except\nfrom Texas. A member of one of the\nlargest grain firms in Chicago reported\nafter a personal survey of the country\nfrom Chicago to St. Louis that the\ncorn crop situation is \u201cheart breaking\u201d\nand that there are hundreds of fields\nwhich will be out of service. Advices\nwere also at hand that throughout a\nlarge section of lowa, the banner com\nstate, fully 50 per cent of the crop as\nyet is not over three inches tall. Oats\ntrade was sluggish and the market was\ngoverned almost entirely by the action\nof corn.\nProvisions were held steady by firm\nness of the hog market.","height":"24861","width":"19191"}}
